  "description": "A police officer stops you on the sidewalk, has no warrant, and has not seen a crime. Can he still frisk you?\n\nThis episode explains Terry v. Ohio, the 1968 Supreme Court case that created the modern rule for brief street stops and weapons-only frisks based on reasonable suspicion.\n\nVisual note: this video uses AI-generated symbolic reconstructions and motion graphics. They are not authentic footage, and no real-person likeness is intended.\n\nNext episode: the phone in your pocket.",
